/* KCNA content - Cloud Native Application Delivery (16% of exam). Auto-generated. */
KCNA.register({"id": "delivery", "name": "Cloud Native Application Delivery", "weight": 16, "notes": [{"id": "delivery-note-1", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "title": "Application Delivery Fundamentals", "html": "<p>Application delivery is the end-to-end practice of getting code from a developer's machine into a running, observable workload in a cluster, repeatedly and safely.</p><ul><li><strong>Build</strong>: source code is compiled and packaged into an immutable <strong>container image</strong>, then pushed to a <strong>registry</strong> (e.g. Docker Hub, GHCR, Harbor).</li><li><strong>Release/Deploy</strong>: the image is referenced by a Kubernetes manifest (<code>Deployment</code>, <code>StatefulSet</code>) and applied to the cluster.</li><li><strong>Declarative model</strong>: you declare the <em>desired state</em> in YAML; controllers reconcile actual state toward it. This is the foundation of all cloud native delivery.</li><li><strong>Immutability</strong>: never patch a running container. Build a new image with a new tag and roll it out. Avoid the <code>latest</code> tag in production (non-deterministic).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip — deployment strategies</strong>: <strong>Rolling update</strong> (default for <code>Deployment</code>, gradual replacement, no downtime); <strong>Recreate</strong> (kill all, then start new, causes downtime); <strong>Blue-Green</strong> (two full environments, switch traffic); <strong>Canary</strong> (route a small % of traffic to the new version first).</li><li><strong>Rollbacks</strong>: <code>Deployment</code> keeps revision history; <code>kubectl rollout undo</code> reverts.</li><li><strong>12-Factor App</strong> principles (config in env, stateless processes, disposability) underpin cloud native delivery.</li><li>Goal of good delivery: <strong>repeatability, reliability, speed, and safe rollback</strong>.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "delivery-note-2", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD concepts and pipelines", "title": "CI/CD Concepts and Pipelines", "html": "<p>CI/CD automates the path from a code commit to a deployed workload, replacing manual, error-prone steps with a repeatable pipeline.</p><ul><li><strong>CI (Continuous Integration)</strong>: every commit is automatically built and tested. Catches integration bugs early, keeps <code>main</code> always releasable.</li><li><strong>CD</strong> has two meanings: <strong>Continuous Delivery</strong> (every change is automatically prepared/staged but a human approves the production release) vs <strong>Continuous Deployment</strong> (every passing change goes to production with no manual gate).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Typical pipeline stages</strong>: source/commit &rarr; build image &rarr; test (unit/integration) &rarr; scan (vulnerabilities, lint) &rarr; push to registry &rarr; deploy.</li><li><strong>Pipeline as code</strong>: the pipeline definition lives in the repo (e.g. <code>.gitlab-ci.yml</code>, GitHub Actions workflow), versioned alongside the app.</li><li><strong>CNCF tools</strong>: <strong>Tekton</strong> (Kubernetes-native CI/CD using <code>Task</code> and <code>Pipeline</code> CRDs, runs each step as a pod), <strong>Argo Workflows</strong>, plus ecosystem tools like Jenkins, GitLab CI, GitHub Actions.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip</strong>: CI/CD is <strong>push-based</strong> — the pipeline has credentials and pushes changes <em>into</em> the cluster (<code>kubectl apply</code>). Contrast with GitOps, which is <strong>pull-based</strong>.</li><li><strong>Tekton vs Argo Workflows</strong>: both run pipelines as pods in-cluster; Tekton focuses on CI/CD building blocks, Argo Workflows is a general DAG/workflow engine.</li><li>Benefits: faster feedback, fewer manual errors, consistent and auditable releases.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "delivery-note-3", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "title": "GitOps: Argo CD & Flux", "html": "<p><strong>GitOps</strong> uses a Git repository as the single source of truth for declarative infrastructure and apps; an in-cluster agent continuously reconciles the cluster to match Git.</p><ul><li><strong>Four GitOps principles</strong>: (1) <strong>Declarative</strong> — desired state expressed as data; (2) <strong>Versioned & immutable</strong> — stored in Git; (3) <strong>Pulled automatically</strong> — agents pull approved state; (4) <strong>Continuously reconciled</strong> — drift is detected and corrected.</li><li><strong>Pull-based</strong>: the agent runs <em>inside</em> the cluster and pulls from Git. The cluster's credentials never leave it — more secure than push-based CI/CD. <strong>Exam tip</strong>: GitOps = pull; classic CI/CD = push.</li><li><strong>Reconciliation loop</strong>: agent compares Git (desired) vs cluster (actual), reports <em>drift</em>, and applies changes. Reverting a bad change = a Git revert.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Argo CD</strong>: GitOps controller with a rich UI/CLI. Core CRD is <code>Application</code> (maps a Git path to a cluster/namespace). Shows sync status (Synced/OutOfSync) and health; supports manual or automated sync and self-heal.</li><li><strong>Flux</strong> (CNCF graduated): a set of controllers (GitOps Toolkit) — <code>GitRepository</code>, <code>Kustomization</code>, <code>HelmRelease</code>. CLI-driven, no built-in UI; composable and lightweight.</li><li>Both are <strong>CNCF graduated</strong> and natively support <strong>Helm</strong> and <strong>Kustomize</strong> sources.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Benefits</strong>: auditable Git history, easy rollback, drift correction, separation of CI (build/push image) from CD (GitOps deploys).</li></ul>"}, {"id": "delivery-note-4", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging and templating with Helm and Kustomize", "title": "Helm & Kustomize Packaging", "html": "<p>Helm and Kustomize both produce Kubernetes manifests but take opposite approaches: Helm <strong>templates</strong> and packages, Kustomize <strong>overlays</strong> plain YAML.</p><ul><li><strong>Helm</strong> is the <em>package manager</em> for Kubernetes (CNCF graduated). A package is a <strong>chart</strong>.</li><li><strong>Chart structure</strong>: <code>Chart.yaml</code> (metadata), <code>values.yaml</code> (default config), and <code>templates/</code> (Go-templated manifests using <code>{{ .Values.x }}</code>).</li><li><strong>Release</strong>: an installed instance of a chart; Helm v3 tracks release state as Secrets in-cluster (no Tiller — removed in v3).</li><li>Key commands: <code>helm install</code>, <code>helm upgrade</code>, <code>helm rollback</code>, <code>helm template</code> (render only). Charts are shared via chart <strong>repositories</strong> or OCI registries.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Kustomize</strong> is <strong>template-free</strong>; built into <code>kubectl</code> (<code>kubectl apply -k</code>).</li><li>Uses a <strong>base + overlays</strong> model driven by <code>kustomization.yaml</code>: a shared base is customized per environment (dev/staging/prod) via patches, <code>namePrefix</code>, <code>commonLabels</code>, and image overrides — without copying YAML.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip</strong>: Helm = templating + packaging + versioned releases + lifecycle management; Kustomize = patch/overlay plain YAML, no templating language, native to kubectl.</li><li>They can be combined; both Argo CD and Flux natively support each.</li></ul>"}], "flashcards": [{"id": "delivery-fc-1", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "front": "In cloud native delivery, what is the difference between imperative and declarative configuration?", "back": "Imperative tells the system the exact commands/steps to run to reach a state (e.g. 'kubectl run'). Declarative describes the desired end state in manifests and lets Kubernetes controllers reconcile actual state toward it. Kubernetes is fundamentally declarative."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-2", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "front": "What is a Kubernetes controller's reconciliation loop?", "back": "A control loop that continuously observes the cluster's actual state, compares it to the desired state stored in etcd, and takes action to converge actual toward desired. This is the core mechanism behind self-healing and declarative delivery."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-3", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "front": "What does 'desired state' mean and where is it stored in Kubernetes?", "back": "Desired state is the intended configuration of objects (replicas, image, config) declared by the user. The API server persists it in etcd, the cluster's key-value datastore, which acts as the single source of truth."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-4", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "front": "What is the role of a container registry in application delivery?", "back": "A container registry stores and distributes versioned container images (e.g. Docker Hub, GHCR, Harbor). CI builds and pushes images there; the kubelet pulls them at deploy time based on the image reference in the pod spec."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-5", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Application delivery fundamentals", "front": "What is the difference between rolling update and recreate deployment strategies in Kubernetes?", "back": "RollingUpdate (the default for Deployments) incrementally replaces old pods with new ones to maintain availability. Recreate terminates all old pods first, then creates new ones, causing downtime but avoiding two versions running simultaneously."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-6", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD concepts and pipelines", "front": "What do CI and CD stand for, and how do they differ?", "back": "CI is Continuous Integration: frequently merging code and automatically building/testing it. CD is Continuous Delivery (changes are automatically prepared/validated for release, with a manual gate to production) or Continuous Deployment (every passing change is automatically released to production with no manual gate)."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-7", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD concepts and pipelines", "front": "What is a CI/CD pipeline?", "back": "An automated sequence of stages (build, test, scan, package, deploy) that code passes through from commit to production. Each stage gates progression, providing fast feedback and consistent, repeatable releases."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-8", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD concepts and pipelines", "front": "What is Tekton in the CNCF CI/CD ecosystem?", "back": "Tekton is a CNCF Kubernetes-native CI/CD framework that defines pipelines as Kubernetes Custom Resources (Tasks, Pipelines, PipelineRuns). Each step runs in its own container/pod, so pipelines execute directly on the cluster."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-9", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD concepts and pipelines", "front": "Why are container images typically tagged immutably (e.g. by Git SHA or version) in CI/CD?", "back": "Immutable, unique tags ensure each build is uniquely identifiable and reproducible, so deployments are traceable and rollbacks are reliable. Mutable tags like 'latest' are discouraged because they can silently change what gets deployed."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-10", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "front": "What is GitOps?", "back": "An operating model where a Git repository is the single source of truth for declarative infrastructure and application config. An in-cluster agent continuously reconciles the live cluster state to match Git, so changes are made via Git commits/PRs rather than direct kubectl commands."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-11", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "front": "What is the difference between push-based and pull-based delivery, and which does GitOps use?", "back": "Push-based: an external CI system pushes changes into the cluster (needs cluster credentials outside it). Pull-based: an agent inside the cluster pulls desired state from Git and applies it. GitOps favors the pull-based model for better security and drift correction."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-12", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "front": "What is Argo CD and what is its core custom resource?", "back": "Argo CD is a CNCF declarative GitOps continuous delivery tool for Kubernetes. Its central CR is the Application, which maps a Git source (repo/path/revision) to a destination cluster/namespace, and it shows sync status (Synced/OutOfSync) and health."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-13", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "front": "What is Flux (Flux CD)?", "back": "Flux is a CNCF GitOps toolkit for Kubernetes built from composable controllers (source-controller, kustomize-controller, helm-controller, notification-controller). It continuously pulls from Git/Helm/OCI sources and reconciles the cluster to the declared state."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-14", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps with Argo CD and Flux (declarative, pull-based reconciliation)", "front": "In GitOps, what is configuration drift and how is it handled?", "back": "Drift is when the live cluster state diverges from the desired state in Git (e.g. a manual kubectl edit). The GitOps agent detects this (marks it OutOfSync) and, if auto-sync/self-heal is enabled, reverts the cluster back to match Git."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-15", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging and templating with Helm and Kustomize", "front": "What is Helm and what is a Helm chart?", "back": "Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes. A chart is a versioned bundle of templated Kubernetes manifests plus metadata; installing a chart with a set of values creates a release. Charts enable reusable, parameterized, distributable application packaging."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-16", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging and templating with Helm and Kustomize", "front": "What is the role of values.yaml in a Helm chart?", "back": "values.yaml supplies the default configuration values that Helm injects into the chart's Go templates at render time. Users override these values (via --set or a custom values file) to customize a release without editing the templates themselves."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-17", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging and templating with Helm and Kustomize", "front": "What is Kustomize and how does it differ fundamentally from Helm?", "back": "Kustomize is a template-free tool (built into kubectl via -k) that customizes plain YAML using a base plus overlays that patch it per environment. Unlike Helm, it uses no templating language or variable substitution -- it layers declarative patches over existing manifests."}, {"id": "delivery-fc-18", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging and templating with Helm and Kustomize", "front": "In Kustomize, what is the relationship between a 'base' and an 'overlay'?", "back": "A base holds common, environment-agnostic manifests. An overlay references that base and applies patches (e.g. replica counts, image tags, namespaces) for a specific environment like dev or prod, promoting reuse without duplicating full YAML."}], "questions": [{"id": "delivery-q-1", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Declarative vs Imperative", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Kubernetes is fundamentally built around a declarative model for application delivery. What does this mean in practice?", "options": ["You specify the desired end state of your resources, and controllers continuously work to make the actual state match it", "You issue a precise ordered sequence of commands that the cluster executes exactly once", "You must manually restart Pods whenever their actual state drifts from what you intended", "The API server only accepts changes during scheduled maintenance windows"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "In the declarative model you describe the desired state (e.g., in a manifest), and Kubernetes controllers continuously reconcile actual state toward it. Issuing an exact step-by-step sequence of commands is the imperative model, which is the opposite of how Kubernetes is designed to operate."}, {"id": "delivery-q-2", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Self-healing / Reconciliation", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "An application is defined with a Deployment requesting 3 replicas. A node fails and one of its Pods is lost. What does Kubernetes do automatically?", "options": ["It schedules a replacement Pod to restore the count back to 3 replicas", "It waits for an administrator to manually re-create the missing Pod", "It permanently scales the Deployment down to 2 replicas to match reality", "It deletes the Deployment because its desired state can no longer be met"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Deployment manages a ReplicaSet whose controller continuously reconciles actual state to the desired replica count, so it creates a replacement Pod to restore the requested 3 replicas. This self-healing behavior is automatic and requires no manual intervention or permanent downscaling."}, {"id": "delivery-q-3", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Managing Workloads with kubectl", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which kubectl command applies the configuration defined in a manifest file to a cluster, creating or updating resources to match it?", "options": ["kubectl apply -f app.yaml", "kubectl get -f app.yaml", "kubectl describe -f app.yaml", "kubectl logs -f app.yaml"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "kubectl apply -f applies a manifest declaratively, creating resources or reconciling existing ones toward the file's desired state. 'get' and 'describe' only read state, and 'logs' streams container logs (its -f flag means 'follow', not 'file')."}, {"id": "delivery-q-4", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Packaging with Helm", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A team wants to package a multi-resource application (Deployment, Service, ConfigMap) into a single versioned, templated, reusable unit that can be installed and upgraded with configurable values. Which CNCF tool is purpose-built for this?", "options": ["Helm, using a chart", "containerd, using an image", "etcd, using a snapshot", "kube-proxy, using an iptables rule"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Helm packages related Kubernetes manifests into a versioned, templated chart with configurable values, making install and upgrade repeatable. containerd is a container runtime, etcd is the cluster datastore, and kube-proxy handles Service networking; none of those package applications for delivery."}, {"id": "delivery-q-5", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes the core principle of GitOps for application delivery?", "options": ["A Git repository is the single source of truth for desired state, and an agent continuously reconciles the cluster to match what is committed", "Developers SSH directly into nodes to push application updates manually", "Configuration lives only in the cluster's etcd and is never version-controlled", "Container images are built inside the Kubernetes API server on every commit"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "GitOps uses a Git repo as the declarative source of truth, with an automated agent (e.g., Argo CD or Flux) that continuously reconciles the live cluster to the committed state. Manual SSH pushes and unversioned, etcd-only configuration are exactly the practices GitOps replaces."}, {"id": "delivery-q-6", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Controllers and Operators", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "How does the Operator pattern extend Kubernetes' native application delivery model?", "options": ["It packages domain-specific operational knowledge into a custom controller that reconciles Custom Resources, automating Day-2 tasks for an application", "It replaces the kube-scheduler so Pods are placed without considering resource requests", "It is a standalone GUI that submits manifests to the API server on a human's behalf", "It bypasses the Kubernetes API server to write desired state directly into etcd"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "An Operator combines Custom Resource Definitions with a custom controller that encodes app-specific operational logic, extending the reconciliation model to automate complex Day-2 operations like backups, scaling, and upgrades. It does not replace the scheduler, act as a mere GUI, or bypass the API server to write to etcd directly."}, {"id": "delivery-q-7", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CI/CD Fundamentals", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In a CI/CD pipeline, what does the \"CI\" (Continuous Integration) stage primarily focus on?", "options": ["Frequently merging developers' code changes into a shared repository and automatically building and testing them", "Automatically deploying every approved release to production servers without human review", "Continuously monitoring running production workloads for performance regressions", "Provisioning the underlying cloud infrastructure that the application will run on"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Continuous Integration is about merging code changes often into a shared mainline and automatically building and testing them to catch integration problems early. Automated deployment to production describes Continuous Deployment, and infrastructure provisioning and production monitoring are separate concerns."}, {"id": "delivery-q-8", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Continuous Delivery vs. Deployment", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the key distinction between Continuous Delivery and Continuous Deployment?", "options": ["Continuous Delivery keeps every change release-ready but requires a manual approval to push to production, while Continuous Deployment releases every passing change to production automatically", "Continuous Delivery only builds artifacts, while Continuous Deployment only runs tests", "Continuous Delivery applies to stateless apps, while Continuous Deployment applies only to stateful databases", "Continuous Delivery runs in a CI server, while Continuous Deployment can only run inside Kubernetes"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "In Continuous Delivery, every change that passes automated checks is kept deployable but a human gives final approval before production; in Continuous Deployment, every change that passes automated tests is released to production with no manual gate. The other options misstate the difference."}, {"id": "delivery-q-9", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In the GitOps approach to continuous delivery for Kubernetes, what serves as the single source of truth for the desired state of the cluster?", "options": ["A Git repository containing declarative configuration manifests", "The kubelet's local cache on each worker node", "An imperative shell script run manually by an operator", "The container registry storing the application images"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "GitOps uses a Git repository of declarative manifests as the single source of truth; an agent (such as Argo CD or Flux) continuously reconciles the live cluster state to match Git. A container registry stores images, not the desired cluster state, and imperative scripts contradict the declarative GitOps model."}, {"id": "delivery-q-10", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "CNCF CD Tooling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which pair of CNCF projects are commonly used to implement GitOps-based continuous delivery to Kubernetes?", "options": ["Argo CD and Flux", "Prometheus and Grafana", "Envoy and Linkerd", "etcd and CoreDNS"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Argo CD and Flux are CNCF continuous delivery tools that implement GitOps by reconciling cluster state with Git. Prometheus/Grafana are observability tools, Envoy/Linkerd handle networking and service mesh, and etcd/CoreDNS provide cluster data storage and DNS."}, {"id": "delivery-q-11", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Pipeline Concepts", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the main purpose of running an automated test suite as a stage within a CI/CD pipeline?", "options": ["To automatically detect defects early and prevent broken code from progressing toward production", "To increase the size of the final container image for redundancy", "To replace the need for a version control system", "To manually approve each commit before it is merged"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Automated testing in a pipeline gives fast feedback so defects are caught early and faulty changes are stopped before they reach production. It does not replace version control, does not add image bloat, and automation is the opposite of manual per-commit approval."}, {"id": "delivery-q-12", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Reconciliation", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team uses a GitOps controller running inside the cluster. An operator manually edits a Deployment with kubectl, changing the replica count, but the value in the Git repository is unchanged. Assuming a typical pull-based GitOps setup with self-healing enabled, what is the expected behavior?", "options": ["The controller detects the drift and reconciles the live Deployment back to the replica count declared in Git", "The manual change becomes the new desired state and is automatically committed back to Git", "The controller permanently disables itself because manual changes were detected", "The cluster ignores Git from then on and trusts only the manually applied value"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A pull-based GitOps controller with self-healing continuously reconciles live state to the desired state in Git, so out-of-band manual changes are treated as drift and reverted to match the repository. GitOps does not auto-commit live changes back to Git, nor does it abandon Git as the source of truth."}, {"id": "delivery-q-13", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Principles", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In a GitOps workflow, what serves as the single source of truth for the desired state of the cluster?", "options": ["A Git repository containing declarative configuration", "The live state stored in the cluster's etcd datastore", "A CI server's build artifacts and logs", "An imperative shell script run by an operator"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The defining GitOps principle is that a Git repository holds the declarative desired state and acts as the single source of truth. etcd reflects the live (actual) state that GitOps continuously reconciles toward the Git-declared desired state, so it is not the source of truth."}, {"id": "delivery-q-14", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Reconciliation Model", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Tools like Argo CD and Flux are described as using a 'pull-based' deployment model. What does this mean?", "options": ["An in-cluster agent pulls the desired state from Git and applies it to the cluster", "A CI pipeline pushes manifests to the cluster using kubectl apply", "Developers manually pull images from a registry onto each node", "The cluster pulls container logs back to a central Git server"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "In the pull-based model, an agent running inside the cluster continuously pulls (fetches) the desired state from Git and reconciles the cluster to match it. This contrasts with push-based CI pipelines that use external credentials to push changes into the cluster."}, {"id": "delivery-q-15", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Drift Detection", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "An operator uses kubectl to manually scale a Deployment that is managed by Argo CD. What does Argo CD report about this application?", "options": ["The application is OutOfSync because live state differs from Git", "The application is automatically deleted to protect the cluster", "The change is committed back to Git to update the source of truth", "Nothing, because Argo CD only checks state at initial deployment"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Argo CD continuously compares live cluster state against the desired state in Git. A manual change creates drift, so the application is reported as OutOfSync. GitOps tools reconcile from Git to cluster; they do not write live changes back to Git."}, {"id": "delivery-q-16", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Self-Healing", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "With automated sync and self-healing enabled, how does a GitOps controller respond when it detects that the live cluster state has drifted from the desired state in Git?", "options": ["It re-applies the manifests from Git to revert the cluster back to the desired state", "It updates the Git repository to match the current live cluster state", "It pauses all reconciliation until an operator manually approves", "It rolls back the Git history to the previous commit"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Self-healing means the controller automatically re-applies the Git-declared desired state to correct drift, restoring the cluster to match Git. GitOps treats Git as authoritative, so it never overwrites Git with live cluster state."}, {"id": "delivery-q-17", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Tooling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Argo CD and Flux are both CNCF Graduated projects in which category of cloud native tooling?", "options": ["Continuous delivery / GitOps for Kubernetes", "Container runtimes (CRI implementations)", "Service mesh data planes", "Distributed tracing backends"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Argo CD and Flux are both CNCF Graduated projects focused on continuous delivery and GitOps for Kubernetes. They are not container runtimes, service meshes, or tracing systems."}, {"id": "delivery-q-18", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "GitOps Security Model", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Compared to a traditional push-based CI/CD pipeline, which security advantage is characteristic of the pull-based GitOps model?", "options": ["Cluster credentials stay inside the cluster instead of being exposed to an external CI system", "It eliminates the need for any authentication to the Git repository", "It removes the requirement to scan container images for vulnerabilities", "It encrypts all Kubernetes Secrets at rest automatically"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Because an in-cluster agent pulls changes, the cluster's write credentials never have to be handed to an external CI system, reducing the attack surface. GitOps does not remove the need for Git authentication, image scanning, or separate Secret encryption."}, {"id": "delivery-q-19", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Helm Fundamentals", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In the Helm ecosystem, what is the standard term for the packaged unit that bundles all the Kubernetes resource templates and metadata needed to deploy an application?", "options": ["A chart", "A manifest", "A pod", "A kustomization"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Helm chart is the packaging format that contains templated Kubernetes manifests plus metadata (Chart.yaml, values.yaml, templates/). A 'manifest' is just a rendered YAML resource definition, a 'pod' is a single workload object, and 'kustomization' belongs to the Kustomize tool, not Helm."}, {"id": "delivery-q-20", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Helm Values", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "How does Helm allow a user to customize a chart's configuration without editing the chart's templates directly?", "options": ["By overriding parameters through a values file (values.yaml) or --set flags", "By editing the rendered manifests in etcd directly", "By patching each resource with a separate kubectl command after install", "By recompiling the chart binary with new defaults"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Helm separates configuration from templates: defaults live in values.yaml and users override them via a custom values file (-f) or --set on the command line. Charts are not compiled binaries, etcd is not edited directly, and customization happens at render time rather than by manually patching live objects."}, {"id": "delivery-q-21", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Kustomize Approach", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes how Kustomize differs from Helm in its core approach to customizing Kubernetes manifests?", "options": ["Kustomize uses template-free, declarative overlays that patch plain YAML, while Helm uses a templating engine with variables", "Kustomize requires a templating language like Go templates, while Helm uses plain YAML patches", "Kustomize can only delete resources, while Helm can only create them", "Kustomize runs exclusively inside the cluster, while Helm runs only on the client"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Kustomize is template-free: it takes valid base YAML and applies declarative overlays/patches without a templating language. Helm, by contrast, relies on Go-template-based variable substitution driven by values. Both are client-side build/render tools, and neither is limited to only creating or only deleting resources."}, {"id": "delivery-q-22", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Kustomize Bases and Overlays", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A team keeps one common set of manifests and then creates separate folders that patch them for dev, staging, and production. Which Kustomize concept are the per-environment folders an example of?", "options": ["Overlays that reference and modify a common base", "Helm subcharts pulled from a dependency repository", "CustomResourceDefinitions for each environment", "Immutable ConfigMaps generated at runtime"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Kustomize uses a base (shared manifests) plus overlays (environment-specific kustomizations that reference the base via 'resources' and apply patches). Subcharts are a Helm dependency mechanism, and CRDs extend the Kubernetes API rather than implement this layering pattern."}, {"id": "delivery-q-23", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Kubectl and Kustomize Integration", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Kustomize functionality is built directly into kubectl. Which command applies a directory containing a kustomization.yaml to a cluster?", "options": ["kubectl apply -k <directory>", "kubectl kustomize install <directory>", "kubectl helm apply <directory>", "kubectl create chart <directory>"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Kustomize is integrated into kubectl, and the -k flag tells kubectl to build a kustomization directory and apply the result. ('kubectl kustomize <dir>' only renders to stdout without applying.) There is no 'kubectl helm' or 'kubectl create chart' subcommand."}, {"id": "delivery-q-24", "domainId": "delivery", "topic": "Helm Releases and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "When Helm installs a chart into a cluster, it creates a named release and stores its state so the deployment can be upgraded or rolled back later. Where does modern Helm (v3) store this release state by default?", "options": ["In Kubernetes Secrets within the release's namespace", "In a dedicated Tiller pod running in kube-system", "In a local file on the operator's workstation only", "In the chart's values.yaml committed to Git"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Helm v3 persists release information as Secrets (base64-encoded, type helm.sh/release.v1) in the target namespace by default, enabling upgrades and rollbacks. Tiller was removed in Helm v3, so there is no server-side Tiller component, and release state is not kept solely on the workstation or in values.yaml."}]});
